Description.div: On the following pages you will be asked %System_NumberOfQuestions% questions about environmental law generally, including the Resource Management Act (the RMA).

You may be asked three different types of questions: multiple choice, true/false or yes/no. Answer each question by clicking the button to the left of the most appropriate response.
After you answer the last question, you will be given the chance to review and then submit your answers.
Please note that if you Exit the quiz before clicking the Submit Answers button then your answers will not be saved.
To move between questions, use the ◄ and ► navigation buttons on the bottom right of the page.

Description.strong: What is included in the ‘environment’ under the RMA?

Answer.Description: Ecosystems.
Natural and physical resources.
People and communities.
Social, economic and cultural wellbeing.
All of the above.

Description.strong: Bob has recently been getting a lot of calls from contractors who want to store their machines at his depot. Bob has ‘existing use’ rights, which allow him to run his depot, despite the recent re-zoning of his land as residential. Bob now wants to double the amount of machines he stores and maintains. Can he do this without a resource consent?

Answer.Description: Yes. The fact that Bob had been operating continuously for a period before the land was re-zoned, means he can go ahead and make the increase.
No, probably not. Existing use rights only apply in limited circumstances where the effects of the activity are the same or similar in character intensity and scale to Bob’s activities.

Description.strong: Which of the following people have environmental law obligations?

Answer.Description: Directors and managers.
Employees.
Contractors.
All of the above.

Description.strong: Mr Lee is a consultant engineer. He is hired to oversee the construction of a new office building in downtown Wellington. Under the contract, he has a monitoring role and has the power to issue directions to the building contractor (BB Ltd). Mr Lee fails to properly monitor the site and the contractor, BB Ltd, breaches one of the resource consent conditions. Who is liable for the breach of the resource consent?

Answer.Description: Mr Lee, as the supervising consultant, BB Ltd, and its employees are all potentially liable.
The employees of BB Ltd only, being those people who actually committed the breach of the consent.

Description.strong: What is the central purpose of the Resource Management Act 1991?

Answer.Description: To protect the environment against an unreasonable level of development or exploitation.
To promote the sustainable management of natural and physical resources.
To provide for a system of town and country planning and the wise use of resources.
Environmental law can only be enforced by local councils.
It is OK to breach environmental laws if it saves a lot of time and cost.
Local councils, trade competitors, community groups and private individuals can potentially enforce environmental laws.
The RMA is only concerned with environmental pollution.

Description.strong: A person or company convicted of an environmental offence can be ordered by a Court to:

Answer.Description: Do all of the following.
Pay a fine.
Fix (or remediate) any damage they have caused to the environment.
In the case of serious offences, serve a term of imprisonment.

Description.strong: Mr and Mrs Higgins own a dairy farm property, which is run by a farm manager, Terry Johnson. The farm has a discharge consent allowing for effluent to be pumped and irrigated from collector ponds onto adjacent land. A condition of the consent is that overflows into waterways are prohibited. During a routine pumping operation, there is an overflow into an adjacent stream. Terry and Mr and Mrs Higgins are prosecuted under the RMA. Is it a defence for Mr and Mrs Higgins to show that they did not know that this particular operation was going on?

Answer.Description: No, they are the farm owners and are always liable for the actions of any person on the farm.

Yes, although they knew in general terms that their employees were engaged to undertake effluent pumping, they did not know the specifics of this particular operation. They cannot be held liable for the actions of Mr Johnson.

Description.strong: Mr Jackson is a truck driver for Transgoods Limited. He stops to get diesel during a trip and by mistake fills up with petrol. To clear the diesel tank he pumps the petrol out into the forecourt of the petrol station and causes substantial pollution. Both Mr Jackson and Transgoods are prosecuted under the RMA. Can Transgoods Ltd use the fact that it has a staff training program for dealing with spills as a defence to the alleged breach of the RMA?

Answer.Description: Yes, it is a defence for a company to show that it took all reasonable steps to deal with foreseeable incidents.
No, offences under the RMA are strict liability offences and the company is liable for the actions of its employees.

Description.strong: Read the following statement. A director of a company is only liable for the actions of the company under the RMA if he or she knew that an offence was being committed. True or false?

Answer.Description: True, directors cannot be held liable for the actions of the company unless they had actual knowledge of what was occurring.
False, directors can be liable if they should have known what was occurring and failed to take reasonable steps to prevent or stop it.

Description.strong: In what circumstances can a member of a management team be prosecuted for the actions of the company under the RMA?

Answer.Description: Managers are only liable where they have committed the offence personally.

Members of the management team can be prosecuted in exactly the same circumstances as directors of the company (i.e. if they both knew or should have known about the actions of the company and failed to take reasonable steps to prevent those actions from occurring).
Managers can be liable if they knew about an offence being committed, but only if they are responsible for managing environmental risk within the organisation.
